observations.conclusion:
Level 3 features are barely there, could have used them but they could just be a fleck of sweat/dust in the right place.

Degree of similarity - 5   There's not a lot that can be used in the mark but what is there is perfectly clear with no differences.

(C) Degree of Similarity = 4 (no pattern but also no differences) 
(E) Degree of Support = 4

Degree of Similarity - 4
Degree of Support - 4

Due to a lower degree of discriminability, I had to assign the degree of support a 4 and not a 5 even though there are no differences visible to me at all. 
The pattern and location of the core in the print are as I had estimated. 
A limited number of minutiae corresponding but enough in my opinion to ID as those present have high clarity. Ridge shapes and location of minutiae all as expected. 
The distinct break in the ridge at points '5' and '6' are clear. I didn't mark this up initially as I wasn't sure it was a feature or just a break in the ridge which might not be visible dependant on pressure when laid down. 
4 features I marked on mark, but are not visible on the print due to not being disclosed.

Degree of similarity:4

Degree of support: 5

Degree of similarity - 4
Degree of support - 3

(Almost) total similarity
No pattern visible. Third level detail (dots and ridge shape/flow) used to bolster identification seeing as there are minimal features and no pattern

Support for identification - there is a fairly low number of features in agreement and a couple of these are near the edge of the mark. No differences.

Degree of Similarity - 3 Some features correspond but lack of detail on mark in terms of pattern and volume mean that there is only a medium not high degree of similarity
Degree of Support - 4 I support identification, the uniqueness of the break in the ridge coupled with the other features in sequence and agreement surrounding satisfies this conclusion. If there had been more corresponding detail in terms of the known form going high enough it may have been enough to go to 5.

Unable to compare quality of form, if a form captured higher up print identification/exclusion could be made.
